VThe occasion was - Thyagarajaaradhanaand Sivaratri celebrations and the audience was treated to some good music as vocalists presentedkirtanasthat Thyagaraja wrote on Lord Siva. Percussion artistes Kapa Srinivasarao (mridangam), Jayakumracharya (tabla), Janardhan (Ghatam) presentedLaya Vinyasammarking theLingodbhava(birth of Sivalinga) at midnight.. A total of 25 artistes took part inPancharatna kirtanasevaled by Kommanduri Seshadri and Sundari Janakiraman. Among the vocalists and instrumentalists who gave solo performances were Panduranga Sarma, Vyjersy Balsubramanyam, P.V.Subba Rao, Venumadhav, Lalitha Madhav, Duddu Radhika and others. Violin duet by Seshadri and his son Souri Rajan with Jayakumaracharya on mridangam was laudable.This was marked by their presentation ofBrochevarevarurain Khamas andUpacharamu Chesevarunnaruin Bhairavi.Veteran vocalist Sunadari Janakiraman&#8217;s Pantuvarali essay and the rendition ofSiva Sivayanaradain it carried the needed tempo and devotional appeal in expression. Young and eclectic vocalist R.V.Panduranga Sarma too preferred to renderSiva Sivayanarada.&#8217;A research scholar and vocalist Vyjersy presentedAmma Ravammain Kalyani on goddess Tulasi, Venumadhav&#8217;sRara Rajeeva Lochanain Mohana,Nadatanumanisamin Chittaranjani, P.V. Subba Rao&#8217;s rendition ofParidanamichitein Bilahari andCharanamule Nammitein Kapi was preceded by a brief essay of both the compositions. Duddu Radhika&#8217;sTelisiramachintanatoin Poornachandrika andNinuvinain Reetigowla were notable offerings.While Sankara Rao, a young researcher on musicspoke on theSahityaaspect of Thyagaraja compositions,children sangbhajans.
